C. The Cognitive Cockpit and the Evolving Pilot

The F-47 cockpit will be a revolutionary human-machine interface, moving beyond the physical screens and switches of previous generations toward a fully digital, potentially holographic, environment. The pilot's primary interface will be an advanced helmet-mounted display (HMD) that uses augmented reality (AR) to project critical 3D flight data, fused sensor information, and tactical overlays directly into their field of view. Leveraging a distributed aperture system of sensors embedded in the aircraft's skin, similar to the F-35, the HMD will provide a seamless 360-degree view of the battlespace, effectively allowing the pilot to "see through the plane".   



This technological leap will transform the pilot's role from a hands-on operator to a high-level mission commander. Powerful on-board artificial intelligence will fuse data from all available sources, automatically prioritize threats, predict adversary movements, and recommend optimal courses of action. This AI-assisted decision-making will dramatically reduce the pilot's cognitive load, allowing them to manage the complexities of controlling multiple CCAs while making faster, more informed tactical decisions.   



IV. Project Chimera: The Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA) Swarm

Designated "Project Chimera" for this analysis, the uncrewed Collaborative Combat Aircraft are the force multipliers of the NGAD system. These semi-autonomous platforms are designed to provide "affordable mass," extend the reach and lethality of the crewed F-47, and perform high-risk missions, fundamentally changing the economics and tactics of air combat.



A. Concept of Employment and Force Multiplication

The core purpose of the CCA program is to solve the strategic problem of a small, expensive, and exquisite fighter fleet. The Air Force has established a planning assumption for a force of 1,000 CCAs, intended to operate alongside 200 NGAD fighters and 300 F-35s. This approach creates combat mass, presenting an adversary with a complex and saturated battlespace of so many targets that their command-and-control and targeting processes are overwhelmed.   



CCAs are not simple drones; they are versatile, modular platforms designed to perform a wide spectrum of missions. These include air-to-air combat, air-to-ground strike, electronic warfare (EW), targeting, and intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR). They function as distributed extensions of the F-47's own sensors and weapons magazines, allowing the manned fighter to sense and shoot at greater ranges. A primary role for the CCA swarm is to conduct "stand-in" missions that are too hazardous for the crewed platform, such as penetrating dense integrated air defense systems, acting as decoys to draw enemy fire, or absorbing the initial volley of enemy missiles.   



B. Platform Variants and Acquisition Strategy

The CCA program is structured in iterative "increments" to foster continuous innovation and competition. In April 2024, the Air Force awarded contracts for Increment 1 to two vendors: Anduril and General Atomics. This selection was notable because it bypassed several traditional defense primes, signaling a deliberate strategy to invigorate and broaden the industrial base. By choosing Anduril, a newer, software-focused company, alongside the more established General Atomics, the Air Force is fostering a new, more agile ecosystem for uncrewed systems. This competitive, incremental approach is designed to rapidly inject new technology into the fleet and prevent the vendor lock-in that has characterized past programs, ensuring the "Chimera" swarm can constantly evolve to meet new threats.   



